snippet: The death of Abdulkader al-Saleh, who led one of the most effective factions fighting President Bashar al-Assad’s forces, came amid a government offensive.
abstract: Many fear that the death of Syrian rebel commander Abdulkader al-Saleh, who helped organize and lead the Tawhid Brigades, is a sign that whatever cooperation remained between Islamist and secular rebels will disintegrate; Saleh was a rare recognized and accessible leader in a fragmented insurgency.

byline.original: By ANNE BARNARD, KARAM SHOUMALI and C. J. CHIVERS
byline.contributor: Anne Barnard reported from Beirut, Lebanon, Karam Shoumali from Istanbul, and C.J. Chivers from the United States. Hwaida Saad and Mohammad Ghannam contributed reporting from Beirut.

lead_paragraph: The death of Abdulkader al-Saleh, who led one of the most effective factions fighting President Bashar al-Assad’s forces, came amid a government offensive.

headline.main: Death of Pragmatic Leader Further Muddles Syrian Rebellion
